children.subject: hello I'd like to add that 8-12 is an understatement for most people and if you really want to understand stuff well the hw is going to take 20+ hours especially if you plan to submit a good writeup.

If 189 next semester is similar to this semester (which I think it could be), the workload isn't too bad. It's 1 pset every week, with a delay of 2 days to the next pset. psets are typically 3 problems, with 2 very math heavy questions and at least 1 coding question. You should be very comfortable with 70 material, and you should know your linear algebra extremely well. Concepts in the class are taught with the understanding that you have a strong background and won't need to see something several times to get it. Concepts will be taught with a bit of the underlying math, and homeworks will drill the underlying math for you. I'd say homeworks are like 8-12 hours a week, with roughly half the time (at least for me) being writing it up (I solve the problems roughly first and am very slow in writing up solutions neatly and w/comprehensive proofs).

history.content: Is 161 + 189 too much? I've heard 189 is a medium workload class with Shewchuk, but at the same time idk if it would be very hard considering I would be going into the class with just 70 + 16ab under my wing. I really want to take 161 because Security is something that interests me and I could potentially take 261 in the fall if I end up liking it... so what to do? Can the two be taken together and still succeed or it is too hard to balance it out? Should I just take 189 on my senior fall/spring and just pray that the professor that teaches it is not too hard? I'm debating taking them together, given that I am already taking a grad course with an open-ended research project and I might also do research next semester
